A black box in the car?
U.S. road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the decaying highway system, and believe they have found the solution in a small black box that can take place in the dashboard of every car.
The devices that record each mile driven and report the information to the authorities are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and the state planning offices to revise the outdated system to finance U.S. roads.
The usually rather boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have allied themselves with environmental groups and are advocating that the government can use the small boxes to record the miles driven – and possibly where they were driven – and then use the information to calculate tax bills.
The tea party is horrified.
The American Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of data protection concerns.
But while Congress cannot agree on a course of action, several states are no longer waiting.
They are currently examining how they can switch to a system where drivers pay per mile driven over the next ten years.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
This is truly a must for our country.
“It’s nothing we’re only going to possibly use,” said Hasan Ikhrata, Managing Director of the Southern California Assn. of Governments, who plans to record the miles driven by all California drivers in the state starting in 2025.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
The technology for that is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, funded by taxes, is broke.
In America, however, there is not as much fuel as before.
Cars use less gasoline.
The state oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 eurocents per liter) has not risen in 20 years.
Politicians do not dare to raise the tax even by a cent at high fuel prices.
“The fuel tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, an expert on traffic legislation at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a miles-based payment system.
“This is the most useful long-term alternative,” he said.
Bureaucrats call it a mile-based user fee.
Not surprisingly, the idea is well received by urban liberals, because the tax could be used, for example, to influence driving behaviour in such a way that traffic jams and climate-damaging exhaust gases are reduced.
The Californian planners rely on the system in the development of strategies to achieve the state’s ambitious, legally enshrined goals on climate change.
But Pennsylvania Republican Bill Shuster, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also stated that he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also inspired by the idea of having drivers pay by distance traveled.
“This is not a tax that disappears into a black hole,” explains Adrian Moore, Vice President of Policy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers who, in a 2011 report, called on Congress to move towards mile-based billing.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have included 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the push, responding to the concerns of MEPs from rural areas representing people who often have to travel many miles in everyday life on their way to work or to the city.
Nevertheless, several states and large cities are moving in this direction on their own.
The most engaged is Oregon, which currently recruits 5,000 drivers for the country’s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the miles instead of the mineral oil tax to the state.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is considering this as well.
Illinois is testing it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transport ministries of 17 states on the east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida), is currently investigating how to introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the equipment, drivers were skeptical of the idea that the government could track any of their movements.
“Concerning Big Brother and things like that was a big problem,” explains Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and results management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People didn't want it.
When the test arrived, Nevada’s ACLU warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn the tachographs into full-fledged surveillance devices.”
There is no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to capture data on individuals’ daily movements.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that the state can use to track the miles driven, but not exactly when and where.
That, Khan said, would make the public more calm.
Hunting for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup company called True Mileage in California.
The company did not initially step in to help states tax drivers.
Rather, their goal was to gain a foothold in an emerging market for car insurance, where drivers are to pay based on the miles driven.
But the devices she tested are also interesting for road planners, because they do not work with GPS and provide limited information that is regularly uploaded via modem.
“People are more willing to get involved if their speed and locations are not recorded,” said Ryan Morrison, Managing Director of True Mileage.
Some of these public pilot programs have made major mistakes.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to implement this.
In Oregon, the planners are experimenting with giving drivers a number of choices.
You can opt for a device with or without GPS.
Or they don’t choose any device at all and instead pay a lump-sum fee based on the average miles driven by all residents of the state.
Others hope to be able to sell the concept of a suspicious public by equipping the devices with more features than with fewer.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a taxation device that can also be used to pay parking fees, pay insurance only for miles driven, and collect speed data from other vehicles in real time, allowing drivers to avoid traffic jams.
“Car drivers would be motivated to participate by the added value of the system’s advantages,” the city said in a planning document.
However, some traffic planners wonder if all the talk about paying per mile is not just a huge distraction.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area, officials said Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by raising the fuel tax.
An additional one-off fee or an annual fee could be imposed on drivers with hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that use little gasoline, so that they also pay a fair share.
"There is no reason for an operation if an aspirin is sufficient," said Randy Rentschler, the Commission's Head of Legislation and Public Affairs.
When we do, hundreds of millions of drivers worry about their privacy and numerous other things.
