Esa decides on large space missions: missions for billions
Remote planets, gravitational waves or black holes – experts from the European Space Agency must now agree on two major projects that they plan to launch in the coming years.
There were 30 proposals to choose from, five are still in the race.
Far-away worlds.
More than 1,000 planets in other stars have already been found by astronomers.
Whether there is life in at least some of them, no one knows.
The choice is difficult: Should you look for gravitational waves?
Or would you rather explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or searching for Earth-like planets and perhaps discovering extraterrestrial life?
These are the questions that the European Space Agency (ESA) is asking.
For their program "Cosmic Vision", they are looking for ideas for two large space projects that are intended to make decisive progress in research.
The budget for such "L-missions" is about one billion euros each.
The launch is expected to be in 2028 and 2034.
In early September, the elite of European space exploration met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
Thirty ideas were under discussion, five of which have now come to the narrower choice.
Numerous committees review the proposals, check with the researchers.
In the next few days, a final decision will be made by the Scientific Programme Committee.
The Esa has selected a total of four major questions to which the missions of the Cosmic Vision program, initiated in 2007, are to find answers.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and life?
The exact processes for the formation of stars from large gas clouds - and thus also the formation of planets orbiting these stars - are still in proverbial darkness.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has planets, under what circumstances can life arise there?
To answer this question, the space telescope "Cheops" is to be launched in 2017, which will be used to investigate 500 already known planetary systems in our vicinity.
The possibilities are limited, but Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, astronomers could map Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres, searching for "biomarkers": gases that are considered an indication of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question, too, should ultimately provide information on the prerequisites for the formation of life.
An important role is played by the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field as well as the particle radiation emanating from it with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be examined by way of example.
With the "Solar Orbiter", the Esa has already approved a mission of the M-Class (there the budget is about half a billion euros) for this question.
The probe is scheduled to launch in 2017 and monitor the Sun's surface and activity closely.
Jupiter and its moons are also of great interest to researchers.
They want to find out what role the giant planet played in the development of the solar system.
For this purpose, the Esa provides the first of the three L-missions of the "Cosmic Vision" program.
Juice (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) is expected to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, it reaches Jupiter and is to study the atmosphere of the planet as well as the icy moons Europe, Kallisto and Ganymed.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
The universe offers many possibilities to study matter under extreme conditions and thus to investigate whether the natural laws known to us are still valid there.
Perhaps there are also deviations that could lead the physicists to a new theory under which all known laws of nature can be united.
How did the universe come into being and what does it consist of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was created by the Big Bang.
In addition to the common matter of stars, planets and living beings like us, there is dark matter whose gravity holds galaxies and clusters of galaxies together, and dark energy through whose action the expansion of the universe accelerates.
So far, the researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first fractions of a second of the Big Bang, nor what dark matter and dark energy consist of.
With "Euclid", the Esa has already approved an M-Mission, whose launch is scheduled for 2020.
With a special telescope, the probe is intended to study the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time in the entire sky, thus allowing conclusions about the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could do the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the selection process.
In the opinion of many experts, the best chances of obtaining an L-mission have been "E-Lisa", a sophisticated concept for the detection of gravitational waves.
Physicists understand changes in the structure of spacetime that Albert Einstein predicted nearly 100 years ago.
They have not been proven yet.
Elisa could do that, the scientists behind the project hope.
The mission provides a detector consisting of two or three probes that is stationed in space.
Unlike plants on Earth, it could also detect gravitational waves that originated in the Big Bang, thus providing new insights into the origin of the cosmos.
Four other proposals are still competing for the second L-mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena", which is to explore black holes, among other things, "Icy Planets", another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism", a mission to survey cosmic background radiation, and the "Exoplanet Finder", which is to track down and investigate Earth-like planets.
Suggestions for sample transport back from Mars, for exploration of the moon, Venus and asteroids as well as for solar physics have already been eliminated.
