Frontier Airlines charges for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 from passengers wishing to store hand luggage on their flight.
Frontier Airlines intends to charge up to $100 for a piece of hand luggage and $2 for coffee or lemonade, even though the announcement on Wednesday read that passengers should keep the entire can.
The new fee applies to hand luggage in the luggage compartment above the seat, small bags under the seat are still free of charge.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if the fee was paid in advance, and $100 for travelers who paid first at the gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O’Malley said the $100 fee aims to move travelers to take care of the payment in advance.
“We don’t want to calculate that amount,” she explained.
Airlines began charging fees for the first and second checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers who tried to bypass them have therefore packed as much as possible in their hand luggage, which means that the luggage compartments above the seat are often overcrowded.
Fees are one way to get passengers to take less on board.
O'Malley said the new fee isn't really about making money.
These are the most loyal customers of Frontier, who have clearly expressed that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find space in the compartment above the seat.
Passengers who purchase their tickets on the airline’s website do not have to pay.
This means that a passenger may be allowed to carry one piece of luggage free of charge at the gate of Frontier, but the next person may have to pay $100 for a comparable piece of luggage.
O’Malley said Frontier’s website and check-in procedures would be changed so that passengers would be informed of the fee before coming to the gate.
The new hand luggage fee from Frontier does not take effect until summer, an exact date does not yet exist.
Passengers often complain about baggage surcharges and other fees, but airlines like to resort to them.
They argue that the transport of luggage costs money and passengers should pay for this service if they wished it.
Many on Wall Street see the new baggage fees as a sign that airlines are taking enough money to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
However, so far, most have left their fingers on baggage fees.
Spirit Airlines Inc. was the first to charge for hand baggage three years ago, followed by Allegiant Air, also a low-cost airliner.
The only other airline with such a fee is the Hungarian Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the additional fees.
He estimated in a December 2011 report that the Spirit hand luggage fee brings in $50 million annually.
Sorensen, who formerly held a leadership position at Midwest Airlines, recently flew with Spirit and was curious about what he would expect at the gate if passengers were confronted with the company’s unusual hand luggage fee.
“The boarding process was one of the smoothest I’ve experienced in my aviation career,” he said.
I was expecting to see gnashing teeth and handy discussions at the gate.
“The plane was full,” he explained, “and the boarding ran like lubricated.”
Frontier also follows Spirit for the 2 dollars required for coffee, tea, lemonade or juice.
The company stated that passengers who bought lemonade or juice should keep the entire can and refill coffee free of charge.
Water is still free.
US Airways had briefly tried to charge for soft drinks in 2008, but reversed this seven months later, after passengers complained and no other large company followed.
Frontier’s move to charge for hand luggage when passengers don’t buy directly from the airline is the latest initiative to direct customers to their own website.
Airlines pay online travel agencies like Orbitz $10 to $25 per ticket sold.
This provides all companies with an incentive to move passengers to buy directly from them rather than through an online travel agency.
However, Frontier has gone the farthest in this area.
In September, the company began to award only half as many frequent flyer miles when booking through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, the miles were reduced to 25 percent of the flight distance.
A flight booked with a third-party provider with Frontier over 1000 miles therefore brings customers only 250 miles.
Passengers can also reserve seats only when buying directly on the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base at its Denver headquarters, but business is shrinking and the company is losing money.
Revenue declined by 9 percent and flight capacity shrank by just under 13 percent in the first quarter, according to the financial report released Wednesday by its parent company, Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic has tried to get control of Frontier’s finances as part of the company’s sale.
