Canadian aircraft and railway manufacturer Bombardier Inc reported a 15 percent decline in net profit after falling orders and deliveries to aircraft in the third quarter, as well as contract problems in the rail sector.
Bombardier, based in Montreal, also did not publish flight test data for its brand new CSeries aircraft and did not provide new information on whether the aircraft could go into commercial use next September, according to the ambitious schedule.
The maiden flight of the test aircraft one and a half months ago has only been followed by three more launches, which makes it seem questionable whether the test phase is going as planned.
Results were lagging behind forecasts, leading to a fall of over eight percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, lowered his valuation from “outperform” to “sector perform” on Thursday in view of the stock having limited price potential over the next one to two quarters.
