Cocaine-Addicted Lawyer Warning Drug Boss of Police Investigation Must Go To Prison
Basharat Ditta, 42, Shared Information with Underworld Size Neil Scarborough
The lawyer was afraid his secret drug addiction might come to light
He was sentenced to three years in prison by the Liverpool Crown Court.
A well-known criminal defender who warned a drug lord of a major police investigation because he was afraid his secret drug addiction could be exposed was sentenced to three years in prison.
Basharat Ditta, 42, provided underworld great Neil Scarborough with sensitive information about investigations into his drug trafficking activities after being compromised by his own cocaine addiction.
The lawyer, nicknamed “Bash,” was arrested at his home in 2011 after police monitored Scarborough, whom he had represented in a previous drug trial.
Officials watched Scarborough (32) deliver three bags of cocaine to the lawyer's house in Blackburn, Lancashire, while he was at a bar lunch with colleagues.
Investigations revealed that Ditta regularly consumed Class A drugs after tests found traces of cocaine in his hair, his wallet, and credit cards.
Over a period of eight months between January and August 2011, he attempted to obtain illicit information about the arrest of two men on behalf of Scarborough and one of his partners.
All four suspects were then monitored by police as part of a major investigation into the heroin and cocaine trade in Lancashire, Cumbria, Merseyside, Berkshire and West Yorkshire.
Together with 32 other people, they were later arrested after police secured heroin and cocaine worth 1.5 million pounds and 200,000 pounds of cash in a series of home searches.
Ditta, 42, gave information to the criminals because he feared his drug addiction could become public.
Today, Ditta, who works for Forbes Solicitors in Blackburn, was found guilty and convicted at the Liverpool Crown Court after a three-week trial on two counts of impediment to justice.
He admitted cocaine possession in a previous survey.
The lawyer was convicted after police discovered in their investigation into Scarborough that he had been in regular telephone contact with Ditta in February 2011.
Two investigators followed the suspect and saw him go to Ditta's house and put the drugs under the lawyer's trash box with a purity of 60 percent in a black golf glove.
Shortly after delivering the drugs, Scarborough regularly phoned Ditta, who was at the Blackburn Rovers football stadium in Ewood Park at dinner.
The lawyer returned home, picked up the drugs, and then nine communications were exchanged between the two.
In court, it was revealed that Ditta was a “regular consumer” of cocaine after tests discovered class A drugs in his hair, his wallet, and on his credit cards.
Ditta was later arrested but denied taking cocaine, saying he had spoken to the suspected dealer because he was his client, claiming that their discussion was under the “lawyer’s secrecy.”
During his arrest, Ditta took his wallet and tried to remove a number of credit cards, but they were seized and a hair sample was taken from him.
During the police interrogation, he stated that he operates an office at both his private address and at the workplace, and clients would call him at home for legal matters.
In court, it was announced that he had called for significant arrests and informed key actors in the drug trade, some of whom he had previously represented, about what the investigators knew about them.
Prosecutor Anne Whyte said, “A criminal lawyer should know better than anyone else that you don’t break the law.”
Ditta is accused of misuse of his position as a criminal defender because he has engaged too much with certain clients.
The relationship in question is not simply that of a drug dealer, but of a drug dealer who supplies his lawyer with drugs.
Some of his communications were undoubtedly legitimate, for he was the lawyer of these persons.
But this went far beyond the limits of a normal relationship between lawyer and client.
He counteracted the police investigation as much as possible so that they could continue to pursue their criminal activities.
Mr. Ditta brought his profession into disrepute.
He was too close to certain clients, especially Scarborough, and he allowed his independence to be compromised.
Ditta denied any wrongdoing and claimed, “If I were a corrupt lawyer, which I am not, and wanted to share information with Scarborough, I would not wait 15 hours, but do it immediately.”
But after the hearing, Superintendent Lee Halstead of Lancashire Police said: “Mr Ditta took the step from a criminal defense lawyer to a criminal the moment he started acquiring drugs from organized criminals.”
His cocaine addiction led to a hopeless compromise and made him receptive to the motives of leading members of organized crime who commissioned him to obtain valuable information about police investigations.
Lawyers must maintain the highest standards of integrity and provide trust and confidence in the public.
Ditta has betrayed this trust and tried to hide behind the facade of his profession.
The Lancashire Serious and Organized Crime Unit led the investigation against Ditta, which also resulted in a conviction in three cases for cocaine possession and judicial disability, which underlines our determination to bring criminals to justice.
This case should be a warning to criminals and shows that no one can escape the arm of the law.
We'll find you and take you to court.
Scarborough himself was sentenced to 14 years in prison after he pleaded guilty to the conspiracy to trade heroin, cocaine and cannabis.
Thirty-five other people involved in drug trafficking have been sentenced to 153 years in total for drug offences.
