“The law is draconian and very punitive and we reject it,” said Cyrus Kamau, Managing Director of Capital Group, which also includes CapitalFM, one of Kenya’s most respected independent radio stations and news websites.
He said the new media tribunal “will always be biased because it is an extended arm of the government,” and restrictions on content and advertising would damage Kenya’s position in the global economy.
“I hope the President is listening to us and we call on him to reject this bill and send it back to Parliament,” he said.
In contrast, according to The Standard, democracy and freedom of speech in Kenya have suffered “a severe blow” and have been described as “draconian,” according to The Star.
The adoption of the law is part of a series of measures aimed at strengthening national security in the wake of the attacks by armed Islamists on the Westgate shopping center in September.
The Kenyan media drew the anger of the authorities for publishing footage of security cameras showing how the units sent to the crime scene allegedly robbed the luxury mall.
Police chief David Kimaiyo responded by hiring two journalists and a leading media representative to interrogate, even though the subpoena was withdrawn after a scream from the media.
According to the new law, media houses can be charged with a penalty of up to 20 million Kenyan shillings and individual journalists can be charged with up to a million as well as the further risk of losing their professional recognition or being excluded from official press accreditation.
The Tribunal also has the right to confiscate the property of those concerned if a penalty is not paid.
According to the Daily Nation, “a single penalty can push most radio stations into bankruptcy.”
In addition, the newspaper believes that these measures could have a devastating effect on Kenya’s “living blogosphere.”
If they silence the media, politicians could do whatever they want with impunity.
“No one will ever know,” wrote Mutuma Mathiu, a journalist with the nation, calling the Kenyan media a decisive control factor in public life.
“If you leave politicians to themselves, they lead the country into bankruptcy and us back to the time of hunters and collectors,” he said.
The Kenyan legislators have already in the past caused public annoyance.
In May, they voted to reverse the cuts ordered by the National Remuneration Commission and reinstated their solid salaries of about 532,000 shillings tax-free per month – they are among the highest in the world.
