Security concerns in Mozambique are growing in the face of clashes between influential personalities
Thousands of people gathered in the center of Maputo under the watchful eye of the statue of Samora Machel, the state founder and first president of Mozambique, to voice cries of peace in a rare public demonstration.
“We want peace again, we want stability,” said Vanessa de Sousa, Managing Director of an investment company.
For fear of the future of the country, she exchanged her business clothes for a t-shirt with the inscription “We demand security” in Portuguese and joined the crowd on Thursday in the capital’s Independence Square.
For the past two weeks, there have been reports of clashes between government forces and Renamo, which are among the worst battles since the peace agreement over 20 years ago.
Renamo was once a notorious rebel movement, initially supported by white-ruled Rhodesia and later by the apartheid government of South Africa in an effort to destabilize the country’s independent government.
After the peace treaty of 1992, she became an opposition party.
Analysts believe it is unlikely that the country will fall back into a full-blown conflict, but recent events have worried foreign investors and locals.
A lot is at stake for the fast-growing economy, as the discovery of huge gas deposits off the coast and coal warehouses in the northwest could bring in more than $50 billion in investments in the next few years from companies such as Rio Tinto, Vale from Brazil, Eni from Italy and Anadarko from the US.
The ruling Frelimo party, the dominant force since 1975, and Renamo blame each other for the tensions.
Renamo claims the government has provoked the recent clashes by attacking its members in the province of Sofala, a traditional stronghold of Renamo, on October 17.
The attacks on the former rebels escalated when government forces attacked Renamo bases and tried to kill Afonso Dhlakama, the group’s leader, Renamos spokesman told the Financial Times.
The government blames Renamo for the clashes and accuses the organization of attacking soldiers.
President Armando Guebuza has tried to downplay concerns about instability.
Speaking to AFP, the French news agency, he said on Wednesday that Dhlakama considers himself a “loser” who wants “to use all of his remaining forces to prove that he can impose his decisions on the government.”
Both Frelimo and Renamo emphasize that they want to avoid war.
However, concerns have increased since Mazanga was quoted as saying that Renamo abandoned the 1992 peace agreement.
He told the FT that he meant that Frelimo no longer respected the agreement.
“Our vision is to resume negotiations, seriously,” Mazanga said.
Previous talks between the parties have contributed little to resolving the tensions fuelled by a series of clashes this year.
“We have two adult men here (Guebuza and Dhlakama) who are colliding their heads,” says Joseph Hanlon, a lecturer at Open University and Mozambique expert.
None of them is good at negotiating and none is willing to make the necessary concessions.
Renamo, who is pushing for election reforms, has already said she will boycott the local elections in November.
Presidential and parliamentary elections are scheduled for next year.
Some commentators have interpreted the use of force as an attempt by a sickening movement to obtain concessions and financial perks from the government.
Renamo’s electoral successes have been shrinking since 1992, while a newer party, the Movimento Democrático de Mozambique (MDM), founded by a former Renamo member, is likely to improve in the elections.
Mazanga claims that Guebuza – whose resignation is due when his second term ends next year – wants to destroy the country’s democracy.
“He doesn’t want multi-party democracy, he doesn’t want transparent elections, he doesn’t want peace because he doesn’t want to give up the presidency,” Mazanga said.
It is unclear what capacity Renamo has, but it has made disturbing attacks on police stations and vehicles on a major north-south connection.
Most of the battles took place in the province of Sofala, which is a few hundred kilometers north of Maputo, but where Beira is located, the port that mining companies such as Rio Tinto and Vale use to export coal.
In June, Rio interrupted the use of the railroad for a month after Renamo announced an attack on the track.
Mazanga replied cautiously to the question whether Renamo would repeat this threat.
Renamo wanted to “warn the international community that things are not going well in Mozambique,” Mazanga said.
The instability has increased the frustration about the government, says Fernando Lima, head of Mediacoop, an independent media company, because many people were already worried about corruption, sluggish progress in development and a recent wave of kidnappings.
“People think that the government and the president are responsible for the future of the country and that he should be the one who finds solutions to the problems,” he said.
Omar Sultane, a protester, said people just wanted stability.
“No one cares about Renamo and Frelimo, they just want peace and usable roads again,” he said.
