What happens to my email on the go?
Email is actually an electronic letter.
Was e-mail technically implemented in the design of the Internet service similar to the traditional mail?
In the conception of the early Internet services, the focus was on making communication possible.
Therefore, the basic technical protocols have not been taken into account to provide a stable foundation for a hearing-proof correspondence.
Therefore, a conventional e-mail is more like an open postcard than a sealed letter.
If user "Anna" sends an email to "Benni", are the computers of the two directly connected?
The email program or browser of Anna sends the mail to the mail server of its service provider in the first step.
For example, if you have a Gmail account, it would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider that Benni uses.
On the track, the mail can run over a number of other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content to his provider.
Are traditional emails read along the way?
Most e-mails are read several times by software robots on the go.
The sender's provider usually checks whether the mail carries a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also carried out on the receiver systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is an annoying and unwanted spam email that is deleted immediately or at least sorted away into a spam folder.
Do the robots have another task?
For systems like GMail, the robot also determines the information Google needs to place contextual advertising.
If Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their upcoming holiday trip, Google can show appropriate links to holiday offers.
Do unknown people read emails?
The likelihood of unauthorized people reading an email is extremely low.
Theoretically, however, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read electronic mail.
Law enforcement agencies and intelligence agencies also have legal opportunities to intercept or take note of emails.
In addition, there are possible illegal scrutiny actions.
Is it possible to protect emails from reading?
With an encryption according to the OpenPGP standard, an e-mail can be effectively encrypted against reading along.
With high technical effort, it is also possible to obscure the metadata of an e-mail communication, so that it is not even possible to easily recognize who communicated with whom.
How important are Yahoo and Google in the e-mail market in Germany?
