Not really a story.
And one that has come so far that it’s already like a fossil: The first time I heard the “independence means passport control” duck at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient story.
Why should one expect an independent Scotland to dance after the European pipe?
Why exchange the London yoke for that of Brussels, especially now?
These are the real European news: the great post-war plan for the unification of Europe has stalled.
With the euro crisis, the European project officially died.
All over the EU, parties are gaining ground that are hostile to the EU or want to throw the euro overboard as a common currency.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Party Alternative for Germany – founded just this year – was able to gain almost five million votes in the Bundestag election in September and thus effectively expel the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
However, the current economic crisis turns out to be a turning point.
Due to the strict austerity policy imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank in connection with the forced jacket into which the respective national economy is forced by sticking to the common currency, many people believe that the project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits – this was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has nailed its members to exchange rates that are beneficial for German exporters – and German politicians would like to leave it that way.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the local currency, southern Europe will find itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage compared to Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public spending – spurred by Berlin.
Behind the current budget and currency problems lies a deepening European productivity problem.
As a result of the “green” energy directives adopted by Brussels – a code for subsidising French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas compared to the United States.
This is a debilitating cost drawback, as we could already see in Grangemouth.
All the wage statements in the world do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being pushed into the corner by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is looming, especially in France, the EU’s former cheerleader.
After the war, the political elite of France saw the EU as a vehicle with which Germany could be kept in check and Paris could be equated with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy and has pushed Europe’s own economic policy, with which the depressed French economy is struggling.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s right-wing, EU-hostile Front National has just won a decisive after-election, placing the ruling socialists in third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote – a timely warning for the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split in the right spectrum would automatically mean benefits for the left.
What does Le Pen do with its newly gained popularity among the white French working class?
It wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-Community currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections – and that is very possible – then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I want to make: in the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the common currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will become something like the “Europe of (sovereign) nations” favored by General de Gaulle.
Germany and a few of its satellite economies may hold on to the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of flattering itself with the United States.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland in all of this?
We can choose to be a region of (finally) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – including telling Berlin and Brussels what they can do.
I suspect that Scotland could do well in a more relaxed European context if we retain our own currency.
Cooperation with other similarly thinking countries is easier in a non-federated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider doing the same to Norway and maintaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – remarkably – the most successful political movement against austerity in Europe and has won a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and implemented) cuts that Labour Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem coalition were responsible for.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to then get an austerity policy imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: growing up faster
