At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes were relatively normal among American girls and were a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents – usually that’s not a sign that puberty is fast,” Kaplowitz explained.
Apparent indications of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and armpit hair, as well as body odor, appear earlier in girls.
Nevertheless, there was only a slight shift in the age of the menarche (the first menstrual period) in the last 40 years.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, slightly less than 12.75 in 1970.
"When breast development begins, it will take at least two to three years to reach menarche," said Kaplowitz, also author of the book "Early puberty in girls: The essential guide to dealing with this common problem."
Time is the most accurate test as puberty progresses.
It is controversial what actually represents the beginning of puberty, but it is “early ripe” when breast augmentation is accompanied by a growth boost before the age of eight.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates – something a pediatrician can monitor closely.
If progress is faster, tests by an endocronologist may be indicated so that serious problems such as tumors or cysts can be ruled out.
There are treatment methods for delaying early menstruation and defending against another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to growth inhibition and thus small body growth in adults.
The recommendations for drug or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child, the rate of development, the rate of growth and the emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about medications, but he admits: “Suppressing puberty can alleviate behavioral problems and girls’ feelings of being unlike their age mates.”
The other big problem is understandable: parents just don’t want their very young daughters to have the period.
“They worry about the risk of pregnancy or how they handle the hygienic side,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter had her days at ten.
Even though there were first signs and we had talked about menstruation, she wasn’t emotionally prepared.
She came home from school terrified and excited because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many widely published theories about the causes of early puberty.
But there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are causative.
Boys come into puberty similar to girls.
Kaplowitz believes that the most convincing premise is the epidemic of obesity.
He supported conducting a 2001 study on girls between the ages of six and nine, which links body fat to entering puberty.
Other research supports this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white age mates.
There are different explanations for this.
Global seems to be an early puberty influenced by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to the climate to the genes.
Another mystery: Although boys’ facial and pubic hair grows earlier, the trend towards a full-blown earlier puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference underlined the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is widespread even in babies and young children.
“We need to be careful how we identify the true beginning of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to seek advice from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
“This may mean that you have to have a conversation earlier than expected,” Kaplowitz advised.
If you stay calm, the child usually reacts well.
Girls who blossom early need the assurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it occurs earlier than thought.
