Pfandhäuser are booming in Singapore as the middle class crisis has arrived
At a pawn shop in Singapore’s Bendemeer shopping center, Janani Amirthalinga exchanges a gold bracelet, ring and pair of earrings to pay for her daughters’ school fees.
“My husband and I just bought a house, there’s all my money in it,” Amirthalinga says.
Although she earns $3,000 a month as an administrative employee and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not sufficient, she explains.
In fact, the demand in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is increasing – is so high that ValueMax, where it traded, became the third pawnhouse listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
Bounding jewelry is not only a quick way to get money – $1,300 Singapore in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, Singapore pledges charge an effective annual interest rate of 17 percent, just over the 15.4 percent that United Overseas Bank demands, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, pawn houses offer the advantage that there is no need to verify the creditworthiness or proof of income, which is why loans are possible faster than at banks.
This is why millions of people in the region turn to pawn houses after families feel the pressure of rising living costs and increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to a loose fiscal policy in the developed economies, families with lower and middle incomes are looking for liens to offset the difference in stuttering economies.
This week, the rating agency Standard & Poor’s described growing household debt, mainly due to rising mortgages, as a risk factor for Asian banks’ creditworthiness.
Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest domestic debt in Asia compared to gross domestic product.
Malaysia is at the top of the list with 80 percent of GDP, an increase of 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also worried about the high consumer debt in Thailand, which has come out of a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed a continuing export weakness and a decrease in consumer demand.
“Ultimately, in the face of rising costs, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible,” says Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historical highs in gold prices over the past two years have further intensified the trend towards pledging personal items as people take the opportunity to turn the family’s jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged items in the city’s 200 pawn houses are gold.
People say to themselves, "The gold price looks good, let's pledge grandmother's gold chain and get back next month."
The largest Thai pawnhouse operator, EasyMoney, has seen a 20 percent increase in customer growth in its branches in recent months.
The growth in the pledge business is so strong that ValueMax, operator of the Bendemeer branch and 15 others in Singapore, want to expand not only to neighboring Malaysia – where the company operates four houses – but also outside of Asia, according to Yeah Lee Ching, Managing Director of ValueMax.
The company finances this with 60 percent of the $66 million it took this week with the Singapore IPO.
While some lenders have fallen into the crossfire because of high interest rates, Yeah explains that pawn houses not only offer cheaper interest rates than other lenders, but also did not directly increase the debt.
“Customers borrow items they already own, and liquefying personal valuables does not increase household spending,” she explains.
The pawn lending business is increasingly accepted as short-term, secured financing.
Also, not all people who use pawn loans are in financial trouble.
Rich Singaporeans also come to ValueMax stores to pledge gold bars and Rolex watches, earning them up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Customers from all social backgrounds come to us.
“These include wealthy people who borrow for a business or investment in the short term, or small businesses who have to bridge bottlenecks in cash flow,” says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
