FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices in airplanes (but do not have cell phone calls)
Air passengers can now use their electronic devices from departure to landing to read, work, play, listen to music and watch movies, but not make phone calls, according to the new guidelines issued Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the United States.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they will be implemented depends on the respective airline, FAA employee Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Air carriers must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the training manuals of the flight personnel and the regulations for the stowage of the equipment in accordance with the new regulations.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve the extended use of electronic devices very soon," the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers need to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They are not allowed to restart until the aircraft reaches a height of three kilometers and the captain gives the green light.
Upon arrival, passengers must turn them off again and must not start them again before the aircraft has landed.
According to the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are protected against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices even during take-off, landing and on the rolling field, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft that have been upgraded to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the professional flight attendant association, welcomed the changes.
“If the new regulation is implemented safely – and we work closely with the airline – both sides will benefit from it,” Glading said.
To be honest, we’re sorry to have to feel like watchers on this issue.
Internet connections for browsing, exchanging emails, text messages or downloading data under three kilometers were still prohibited, the authority explained.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices in flight mode.
So still no “Words With Friends,” the Scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he had to publicly leave a American Airlines jet for refusing to turn off the device while the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices such as laptops still need to be stowed away, as there is a risk of injury if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile phone calls during the flight are also prohibited.
The regulatory competence for telephone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not with the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices at take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national traffic safety expert on CBS News, said mobile phones were still considered a risk.
“Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they could potentially cause disruption to navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that transmission from the air can also interfere with transmitting masts,” Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate this issue recommended last month that the government allow a wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, the pressure on the FAA has increased to ease restrictions on use.
Critics such as Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill of Missouri argue that there are no valid security grounds for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies say that up to one-third of passengers forget or ignore to turn off the device.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air passengers in 1966, after reports of disruptions to navigation and communication devices by VHF radios carried by passengers became known, which at the time represented the latest technology trend.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA that they do not mind electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering Wi-Fi to passengers for several years when the flight height is reached.
The aircraft adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also less sensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for greater use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices generally emit much less radio radiation than previous generations.
For example, e-readers only emit minimal radiation when you turn around.
However, when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
One of the advocates of easing the restrictions on the use of devices by passengers is Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees loaded a passenger plane full of Kindle e-readers and took a test flight to identify problems, but couldn't find any.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using devices.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he thought the disruption was real, even if the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said there were only isolated reports of pilots calling for disruption of aircraft systems through the devices, and most of them were very old.
However, the committee recommended to the FAA to allow pilots to order the disconnection of the equipment by the passengers in case of instrument landing under poor visibility conditions.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and described them as a reasonable adjustment for travelers who today would be extensively equipped with technology.
“We are delighted that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not inconsistent with safety,” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
