Scientists were able to shed more light on the connection between a dog’s tail swinging and his mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs with their tails were waving more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while it was the left side in nervous dogs.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, said: “It is well known in humans that the left and right brains react differently to stimuli that cause positive or negative emotions.”
Here we have tried to look at this in other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just like in humans, the right brain is responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in the feelings.
To learn more about how dogs react to their species' lateral tail swings, the researchers monitored the animals while these films looked at other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the four-legged friends and analyzed the behavior.
Probably we will soon understand why the tail moves in one direction, in the other.
Professor Vallortigara said, “We showed the dogs movies with dogs – either a true-to-life version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw an otherwise expressionless dog moving the tail to the right (as seen from the perspective of the bubbling dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail tendency was primarily to the left (again from the perspective of the dog waving), then their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs have learned from experience what movements they should be worried about and when not.
He said: "If you have different encounters with other dogs and the swirling with the tail in one direction is more associated with friendly behavior and the right side is more likely to produce less friendly behavior, then you react on the basis of these experiences."
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians, and trainers better understand their pet’s emotions.
John Bradshaw, a dog behavior expert and guest scholar at the University of Bristol’s Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, said this was not the first study to investigate whether left and right are important for dogs.
Last year, a team at the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right when it is a satisfied dog.
Another research paper at the University of Victoria in Canada said: “Dogs are more likely to approach a robotic dog when his ‘tail’ is waving on the left and not on the right rather than getting uneasy – just the other way around than in the Italian study.”
According to his statement, the differences could therefore be that the dogs in the various studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs respond to real dogs could help, he explained.
“While there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two hemispheres are used for different purposes, many of the details still need to be determined – and dogs are no exception,” Bradshaw said.
However, since their behavior can be easily recorded, it will probably not be long before we understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
