Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon, in 1981.
At first, he only had a broken arm, but then an inflammation developed that spread to his brain, causing a hematoma that would affect him for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
We would have brought him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to crowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
“It’s not easy,” Bwelle comments.
You can leave the house at five in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, but you are not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has hardly changed since Bwelle’s father died in 2002.
There is only one doctor for every 5,000 people in Cameroon, according to the World Health Organization.
In contrast, the ratio in the United States is to a doctor for 413 people.
But even if there was a doctor for her, most Cameroonians could not afford to visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of the country’s healthcare spending is private.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” says Bwelle.
Poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
His father and so many of his compatriots suffered in Bwelle made the decision to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and offers free medical care there.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped almost 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people squeeze themselves into minibuses and drive to the villages in need on the roof over unpaved terrain with the constricted medical equipment.
Not always everything goes smoothly.
More than once they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they will be welcomed like heroes: a feast, singing and dancing and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a reason to celebrate and bulge – with its wide smile and limitless energy – is happy to attend the cheerful celebration.
The next morning, the team then begins examining hundreds of patients.
“We treat 500 people per trip,” says Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometers around the village – and that on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites, and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses, or free birth certificates – a document that is required for school, but many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
The surgeries usually take place in a school, town hall, or apartment; after the procedure, the patients get up and go to the recovery area to make room for the next.
The lighting for the operation and the disinfection equipment is fed by the group generator and so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early morning hours on Sunday.
It’s a strenuous pace, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
“They drum all night so we can stay awake and continue our work,” says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team then heads back to the city, tired but proud of the work done.
The group – a mix of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – performed 700 free surgeries last year, knowing that their work makes a huge difference for the people they help.
