“This will change the future of my family,” the man said.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job, he finances 60% of his charitable activity, according to Bwelle; the rest comes from private donations.
“I really don’t know when he’s sleeping,” says Katie O’Malley, who studies medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia and volunteers in Bwelle’s group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so that he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O’Malley, who come from the U.S. and Europe and support Bwelle, this is an opportunity to gain practical experience that they would never get at home.
“We can be involved in surgery where we help drain blood or hold the instruments for Dr. Bwelle,” O’Malley explains.
That would never be possible in America as a medical student in the second year.
Students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and often bring donated medical supplies with them.
But once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes care of the accommodation, transport and guidance.
“He’s without a doubt a hero,” says O’Malley.
He devotes his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no bounds.
For Bwelle, almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to live happier lives and thus fulfilling a promise he gave to his father brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this work,” Bwelle says.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I do.
I do it to make people laugh again and to relieve the pain.
