Tourism: Descent to the Romans
At about 120 meters in length, a sewage canal from the Roman period is preserved below Cologne.
Anyone who visits Cologne will not pass by the cathedral.
About 157 meters, the two towers rise to the sky, making it the second tallest church building in Europe.
But few visitors who admire the two delicate church towers know that there is also a lot to discover under the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in Cologne’s underworld.
The meeting point for his guided tours is the service center of Cologne-Tourismus directly on the cathedral.
The tour begins quite unspectacularly: “We start in the underground car park,” says Schulze.
In the seventies, the city fathers wanted a car-friendly city, and therefore only what was not too large remained of the remains of the old city wall.
Most of the users of the car park rush past the Roman remains and only park their car.
But if you take a closer look, you will discover an archaeological site in Parkdeck D2, separated by metal grid bars.
You can see about five meters high ruins of hand-plate-sized stones.
“It’s the remains of the Roman city wall that was built in the second half of the first century AD,” Schulze says.
Before returning to the daylight, Schulze lets the participants on the upper park level take a look into a dark, 15 meters deep shaft.
This is the fountain of the old cathedral, which is unfortunately hardly noticed.
The next stop of the tour is the Prätorium, and here the participants descend back into the depths.
We see here the office of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the pretor of the CCAA.
A visitor wants to know what CCAA means.
"The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", which in good German means "city of Roman law and city of the Agrippinensians, founded under Emperor Claudius at the site of the altar for the emperor cult".
And the Prätorium is the former governor’s palace, the power center of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the entrance hall of the exhibition leads a tunnel access to the Roman sewage canal, which is preserved here on a length of about 120 meters.
"You can walk along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you want," Schulze cheers the guests.
There's still a surprise for Schulze.
After getting the key at the checkout, he leads the group to a 16 meter deep, walkable shaft.
“We are now in the Mikwe, a ritual Jewish bath,” he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep into the ground to get to the groundwater that was indispensable for ritual washings.
To this day, in the lower end of the Mikwe, whose origins date back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read by changing levels of the Rhine.
The Mikwe will be part of an archaeological zone on the Town Hall Square, for which the construction work is due to begin shortly.
There will be a few more years until completion.
