An American government official who wanted to remain anonymous said Thursday that Israeli fighter planes had attacked an airbase in Syria’s Latakia a day earlier.
The target was “missiles and related equipment” that the Israeli government feared were destined for Lebanese Hezbollah, it said, according to CNN.
Syrian and Lebanese media, as well as Arab broadcaster Al-Arabiya, had previously reported that the base in the port city of Latakia was shelled on the night from Wednesday to Thursday and blamed the Israelis for it.
The Israeli television channel Channel 2 showed satellite images of the base in Latakia, showing Russian S-125 Neva defensive missiles and a battery of SA-3 missiles, which Channel 2 has a range of 35 kilometers and can carry warheads up to 70 kilograms.
Uncertain The government in Jerusalem has not officially confirmed the attack.
However, the Reuters news agency quotes an equally anonymous Israeli government official as saying he believes Israel carried out the attack, but is not sure.
A spokesman for the Israeli Defense Ministry said: “We are not commenting on these reports.”
Journalist Ron Ben-Yishai stressed in the daily Yedioth Ahronoth that the Syrian regime had previously, in part successfully, tried to deliver ground-to-air missiles to Hezbollah.
The Israeli government had repeatedly warned that any attempt by Syria to supply Hezbollah with chemical or other dangerous weapons would signify the crossing of a “red line” that would be followed by a military response.
John Kerry, in an unprecedented admission, said that US espionage had “goed too far.”
John Kerry, with an unexpected admission, hinted at softening the U.S. defensive stance on its surveillance programs, saying the espionage “has gone too far in some cases.”
The Secretary of State also admitted that he, along with Barack Obama, was responsible for switching to “autopilot” when the explosive revelations of whistleblower Edward Snowden about the NSA’s espionage activities became public.
The leaked information has led the U.S. government into a diplomatic storm of indignation on the part of its allies.
At a video-connected speech at the Open Government conference in London, Kerry said: “Without a doubt, the president and I, as well as others in the government, have learned of some things that have happened almost by autopilot, simply because the ability to do so existed, which goes back to the Second World War and the difficult years of the Cold War, and of course, to 9/11.”
He was the first senior member of the U.S. government to acknowledge that US espionage had crossed a border, but also stressed that no rights had been abused.
He said, "In some cases, this has gone too far."
The President is determined to provide clarity and is therefore conducting a thorough investigation so that no one has to feel that abuse is taking place here.
I assure you that the rights of innocent persons in this process will not be affected.
Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a force of good and that many lives had been saved through its surveillance operations.
He added: “We are dealing with a new world where people are ready to blow themselves up.”
There is a radical extremism in the world that is eager to kill people, blow up and attack governments.
So what if you were able to intercept and stop it before it happens?
We actually prevented plane crashes, attacks on buildings and the murder of people because we learned of such plans in advance.
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to alleviate concerns about alleged American espionage and convince Europeans of the need to continue working with the U.S. in the anti-terrorist efforts, the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said on Thursday.
Connecticut senator Chris Murphy said he had spoken to representatives of the European Parliament and other people this week and was concerned about their threats to stop participating in anti-terrorist organizations due to the frustration over National Security Agency surveillance.
“It is very important for the national security interests of the United States that Europeans stay on board in view of our joint efforts against terrorism,” Murphy, who sits in the Senate for the first time as a Democrat and serves as chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on Foreign Relations and European Affairs, said in an interview in Washington.
In addition, I am going to Europe to make it clear that we must continue to cooperate in the fight against terrorism, regardless of their anger over the NSA programs.
Media reports that the NSA has captured millions of telephone data in Europe have strained relations with some U.S. allies, although the head of intelligence said this week that the reports were incorrect and based on a misunderstanding of the metadata collected by NATO allies and exchanged with the United States.
Other revelations cited from documents handed down by Snowden, according to which the NSA had monitored the cell phone of Chancellor Angela Merkel and up to 34 other heads of state worldwide.
The head of national intelligence, James Clapper, defended espionage among allies as necessary, declaring that it was common on both sides.
In all the turmoil, Murphy said his authority was preparing the trip of Congress to take place this year, and hoped the delegation would include members from both parties and chambers.
The names of the other participating members will be published in the coming days.
He said the exact itinerary was still being worked out.
While Murphy stressed that the purpose of the trip was to improve relationships, he also said that there would be some “serious words.”
He said European governments must be honest with their people about the kind of espionage programs they themselves have been using for years.
“Although we can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, they must also accept the fact that we are not the only ones spying,” Murphy said.
Meanwhile, John Kerry is on a trip to the Middle East and Poland this weekend to deal with the resentment about the US strategy in Syria, Egypt and Iran as well as the US surveillance activities.
