Australian woman appeals for imprisonment in Thailand
A 21-year-old woman from Sydney, who was sentenced to 15 days in prison in Phuket for falsely claiming to have been raped by a taxi driver, appealed against the verdict and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was initially found guilty of making a false statement by a Phuket provincial court on June 15 after she told the Thai police that a local taxi driver raped her in the morning hours on Sunday, June 10, while two other men arrested her.
Later, however, the recordings of a video camera showed that she had safely arrived at her hotel after being separated from her Australian friend.
Police in Phuket interrogated Bamford for two days until she confessed to devising the story.
Until the trial, she was in police custody.
Bamford was sentenced to a 15-day prison term in a low-security detention center on the outskirts of Phuket, rather than in a adult women’s prison.
She is the daughter of Peter Tunks, a former player of the Australian Rubgy League, who has turned to the State Department in Canberra to ask for help for his daughter.
Tunks told the Sunday Telegraph in Sydney that the whole family was “extremely concerned” about his daughter’s well-being and wanted her back in Australia.
“We’re very worried, of course, but we hope she’ll be home as soon as possible,” Tunks said.
Bamford has appealed against the verdict and is on a free foot against a bail of 50,000 baht.
In Australian reports it was read that in the meantime she is on holiday in the resort town of Krabi in southern Thailand.
The court heard that Bamford was represented by a local lawyer in Phuket and had been warned that the appeal could also lead to the imposition of a higher sentence of up to two years in an adult prison.
